{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600581/1930101201/0552.xml":{"full_text":"I RARE U. S. ORCHIDS\nI TO BE SHOWN HERE\nFederal Horticulturist Re\ncalls Recent Developments\nIf of Rare Flower.\nThe favored belle, whose popularity\nIs frequently attested by the wearing of\nthat costly floral parasite, the orchid, is\nprobably little aware that she has\npinned to her gown a blossom which\nwas unknown 75 years ago.\nDr. David Lumsden. horticulturist of\nthe Department of Agriculture, who will\nbe one of the judges of the exhibition\nto be held at the Willard Hotel by the\nAmerican Orchid Society Thursday,\nFriday and Saturday, recalls some in\nteresting facts relative to the blossom\nwhich Is now considered the greatest\naristocrat of the flower w\u2019orld.\nCrossing Believed Impossible.\n\u201cThe crossing of flower species was\nI believed impossible 75 years ago,\u201d Dr.\nLumsden said, \u201cand when it was learned\nthat John Dominy, an Englishman.\nwith the firm of Sir Harry Veitch of\nLondon, had successfully proved his\nthedry that a hybrid orchid could be\nproduced from crossing two native\nspecies. Sir Harry exclaimed. \u2018Dominy,\nyou will drive the botanists mad.\u2019\nHowever, Dominy not only did not\n\u201cdrive the botanists mad,\u201d but, accord\ning to Lumsden, he started the intensive\ncultivation of the exotic parasite, which,\ncarried down to the present day, has\nproduced the most Interbred and highly\ncultivated plant in the world. It takes\nsix years, explained the horticulturist,\nto produce an orchid bloesom from the\nplanted seed.\nSome of the flowers which will be\nI* exhibited at the orchid show here are\nthe eleventh generation descended from\nthe blossom which resulted from John\nDominy s experiment in 1853.\nThe orchid, which takes so long to\ncultivate and is of extremely fragile\ncharacter, has now become such a\ncostly flower, that its raising is only\npossible to horticulturists or persons of\nwealth.\nOne Collection Worth $15,000,000.\nOne orchid grower alone, A. C. Bur\nrage of Boston, values his collection of\norchids at $15,000,000. One plant, to\nbe exhibited at the show, is worth\nSIO,OOO, bringing the value of a single\nblossom up to the three and four figure\nmark. In all, the show here will be a\nmillion-dollar affair.\nA particularly interesting exhibit at\nthe show will be that of Mrs. William\ndu Pont of Wilmington, Del., who will\ncontribute some of her famous blue\norchids. There are only two genera of\nblue orchids in the world, and Mrs.\ndu Pont\u2019s specimens will be the only\nFall-blooming species. The blue orchid\nla indigenous to Burma, India.\nA rare feature of the show will be an\nexhibit of perfumed orchids. As a rtile,\nthe orchid is without fragrance, and lor\nthat reason is not always as popular as\nits sisters, the rose or the violet. But\nhorticulturists have now produced an\nexquisitely perfumed orchid by cross\ning an insignificant but highly per\nfumed wild orchid with a cultivated,\nnon-fragrant variety. The perfume is\ndescribed as being a cross between that\nof the fragrant lilac and the lily of the\nvalley.\nSpecial Can Chartered.\nSpecial cars have been chartered by\nDr. George Moore, director of the Mis\nsouri Botanical Gardens, to bring his\nmagnificent collection from St. Louis.\nCut flowers, contributed by Dr. John\nBras ted of Anaheim, Calif., will be\nflown in airplanes from the West Coast.\nCollections exhibited by orchid growers\nof Boston. New York and Philadelphia,\nas well as other Eastern cities, will be\nbrought to Washington in large vans.\nNames prominent in the social and\nfinancial circles of the country will be\nfound among the contributors to the\nOrchid Show. Awards to the value of\nmore than SIO,OOO will be made to ex\nhibitors. A gold medal has been do\nnated by W. H. Jewel and silver cups\nhave been donated by Albert C. Bur\nrage, Mrs. William K. du Pont. Mrs.\nPierre 6. du Pont and Mrs. F. E. Dixon.\nAmong other prizes to be competed\nloi will be gold medals of the Massa\nchusetts Horticultural Society, the New\nYork Horticultural Society, the New\nJersey Florists\u2019 Association, the Ameri\ncan Orchid Society's gold, silver and\nbronze medals and silver trophies. An\nInternational touch will be added to the\ncompetition In the gold medal offered\nby the Royal Horticultural Society of\nLondon. England.\nSpecial awards will be made for the\nmost meritorious exhibit in the show,\nregardless of size; for the best orchid\nflower; for the most original exhibit,\nand for the most artistic exhibit.\nWashington contributors will be Mrs.\nHenry P. Erwin of Abremont, Mrs.\nJoseph Herbert, Charles Seigwart and\nMias Seigwart of Jessup, Md., and Mrs.\nCharles J. Bell. Twin Oaks.\nFirst Exhibition of Kind in V. S.\nThis will be the first exhibition of\nFail flowering orchids ever held in the\nUnited States, the previous shows hav\ning been made up of Spring blooming\nvarieties, and is the first exhibition of\nthe Orchid Society to be held outside of\nPhiladelphia, New York and Boston,\nwhere the Spring exhibitions have been\nstaged in the past.\nThe awards will be made by Clement\nMoore of Hackensack, N. J.; Dr. George\nMoore, director of the Missouri Botanic\nGardens. St. Louis, Mo.: Joseph Manda,\nSouth Orange, N. J.; Edward Roehrs,\nRutherford. N. J.; W. M. Wicks of Wil\nmington, Del., and James I\u2019Anson of\nGreystone. Palisades, N. Y\u201e nationally\nknown judges of the orchid.\nThe exhibition committee in charge\nof the show, of which Prof. Lumsden\nis chairman, includes George E. Bald\nwin of New York. Joseph Manda of\nSouth Orange, N. J.; John W. Blotter\nof Chadds Falls, Pa Oliver Lines of\nPhiladelphia, Pa., prominent members\nof the American Orchid Society, assist\ned by Dr. Earl W. Sheets, Dr. Earl B.\nWhite. J. Marion Shull. Gustav Ander\nson. V. E. Grotlisch, Furman L. Mul\nford. J. M. R. Adams and Axel Somers\nof this city.\nU. S. URGED TO RELAX\nMONROE DOCTRINE\nShould Let Latin American Na\ntions Settle Issues With Europe\nDirectly, Says Professor.\nBy the Associated Press.\nJACKSONVILLE. 111. October 11.\u2014\nProf William S. Robertson of the Uni\nversity of Illinois told the Institute on\nPan-American Relations today that it\nWill probably be better for North\nAmerica to let South American nations\nPght out their own difficulties with\nEurop\"an countries than to invoke the\nMonroe Doctrine.\n\u201cThere have been so many attempts\n\u2022n the part of the United States to\nCanifest its good intentions by the\nonroe Doctrine, which have r?sulted\nIn ill feelings that perhaps if we would\nforget It and let our sister nations solve\ntheir own difficulties they might become\nstronger.\u201d\nThe Institute is being held at Mc-\nMurray College and Is managed by\nChester D. Pugsley of Peekskill, N. Y.,\nbanker-philanthropist.\nHow the North American commercial\ntonoeption of South America has been\nrhanged from \u201crum, molass\u2019s end\nslaves\u201d to comprehension of its real\nposition in world market was told by\nDr. Chester Lloyd Jones of the Uni\nversity of Wisconsin.\n0 Tri-weekly air service between Bris\nbane and Lismore, Australia, has Jurt\nbeen inaugurated.\nRARE ORCHIDS TO BE SHOWN HERE\nI\ns\nm\nW JgPI\nbBIKI\nm y It 1\nnnyfl\nAUGUSTUS KEATON.\nPAINTER, EXPIRES\nSuccumbs to Heart Attack at\nSibley Hospital Dur\ning Trip.\nAugustus Goodyear Heaton, 86 years\nold, celebrated artist, who tor many\nyears prior to 1908 made his home at\n1618 Seventeenth street, this city, died\nearly yesterday at Sibley Hospital from\nheart disease.\nThe body, which is at Chambers fu\nneral home, will be taken by his son,\nDr. D. R. Perry Heaton of Chappaqua; j\nN. Y., to Philadelphia this morning, j\nFuneral services will be held Monday at\n2 o'clock at the La Fayette-Taylor fu- j\nneral home, Broad and Diamond streets,\nPhiladelphia, with interment in the i\nfamily vault at Laurel Hill Cemetery, j\nPainting Hangs in Capitol.\nMr. Heaton, who won international\nrecognition as a painter, achieved the\ndistinction of having one of his paint\nings purchased by the Government in\n1883. This large canvas, known as\n\"The Recall of Columbus,\" is now hang\ning in the Senate wing of the Capitol\nBuilding, gallery floor, lacing the paint\ning of \"The Battle of Lake Erie.\"\nAnother of Mr. Heaton\u2019s paintings,\ncontaining 18 figures, \"Promoters of the\nLibrary of Congress,\u201d is in the local\nYoung Men's Christian Association on\nthe wall of the marble stairway.\nMr. Heaton was en route from his\nSummer home at Black Mountain, near\nAsheville, N. C., on a Northern trip\nwhen he was taken ill. He was visiting\nat the home of his secretary, Mrs. John\nS. Moran, 3521 Thirty-sixth street,\nMount Rainier, Md., when he became\nso ill that he was taken to Sibley Hos\npital. The end came suddenly from\nheart failure about 2 o\u2019clock yesterday i\nmorning. His son. Dr. Heaton, at Chap- I\npaqua. was notified, and arrived yester-\nday afternoon to take charge of ar\nrangements. The artist had planned to\ngo on to Philadelphia to visit friends,\nand then was going to see his son in\nNew York State before returning to his\nhome at West Palm Beach, Fla., for the\nWinter.\nBorn in Philadelphia.\nMr. Heaton was born in Philadelphia\nApril 28. 1844. From 1860 he studied\nat the Pennsylvania Academy of Fine\nArts and under P. F. Rothermel. He ex\nhibited his first picture at the Academy\nof Fine Arts in 1863, and in the Fall of\nthat year went to Paris, where he was\nthe first American to enter the Ecole\ndes Beaux Arts, then first opened to\nAmericans, studying in this school for\ntwo years in the class of Cabanel.\nReturning to the United States, Mr.\nHeaton became art professor and lec\nturer at the School of Design for Wom-\nI en in Philadelphia in 1866 and an as\nsociate of the Philadelphia Academy of\n1 Fine Arts in 1868. and moved to New\nj York, where he resided for several years.\nIn 1878 he went to Paris for the sec\nond time and studied under Bonnat.\nHe exhibited in the Paris Salon four\ntimes, his most notable exhibit being I\n\"The Bathing Hour, Trouville.\u201d Mr.\nHeaton returned to the United States\nlate in 1884 and resided in this city at\nhis studib-home, at the corner of Seven\nteenth and Corcoran streets, until 1908,\nwhen he removed to New York.\nAmong his works are Washington\u2019s\nFirst Mission, owned by the Union\nleague Club, Philadelphia; portrait of\nBishop Bowman, for Cornell College.\nIowa: portrait group of Mr. Tulane and\nSenator Gibson for Tulane University,\nNew Orleans; promoters of the Library\nof Congres*. in the local Y. M. C. A.;\nGraduation Day; The Day Spring frem\non High; Grave of Lafayette, and many\nj portraits and other small pictures.\nPublished Epic Poem.\nAs an author he has published the\nepic poem, the Heart of David, and\nFancies and Thought in Verse, as well\nas Mint Marks, which is considered an\nauthority on that subject. For years he\npublished for the entertainment of his\nfriends a quartely publication known as\nJ the Nut Shell.\nHis picture. \"Hardships of Emlgra\ntion.\u201d is on the 10-cent Omaha stamp.\nSurviving are three sons; Dr. Heaton,\na physician of New York State, who is\nnow here; Augustus Heaton, living in\nFrance, and Harry Heaton, residing\nnear Everett, Washington. Mr. Heaton\nl was a member of the Cosmos Club of\nthis city.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON. D. C., OCTOBER 12, 1930 \u2014PART ONE.\nHeart Attack Fatal\nAUGUSTUS GOODYEAR HEATON,\nEXPOSITION PLAN\nOUTLINED BY DARR\nIndustrial Show Help to Cap\nital Beauty, Radio Audi\nence Told.\nScouting as fallacious the view that\nan Industrial exposition Is a definite\nj step toward conversion of Washington\nj from a city of beauty to one of tower\ning factories, belching chimneys and\n\u201cother accourtrements of an industrial\ncommunity.\" Charles W. Darr, presi\ndent of the Washington Chamber of\nCommerce, In an address broadcast\nover Station WMAL last night, outlined\nplans for the 1930 Industrial Expo\nsition which will be held in the Wash\nington Auditorium the week of Novem\nber 3. The promotion of the exposi\n-1 tion is a definite part of the five-year\nexpansion program recently announced\nby the chamber, Mr. Darr said.\n\u201cThe Washington Chamber of Com\nmerce,\" the speaker said, \"is keenly\nconcerned with protecting the beauty,\ncharm and unique spirit that Is so pe\nculiar to the Capital. Washington, as\nthe Capital City of the United States,\nshould be second to none in magnifi\ncence.\nWork to Be Provided.\n\"At the same time, however,\" Mr.\nDarr said, \"a well balanced community\nmust be able to sustain Itself eco\nj nomically. It must provide work for\nits boys and girls* as well as for Its men\nand women. It must have a firmly\n1 functioning economic structure through\nwhich it can grow and prosper in pro\n-1 portion to the growth and greatness of\nthe Federal Government Itself. That\nthis growth can be accomplished with\nout detriment to the beauty of the city\nand that it can very definitely add to\nthe community's well-being is the con\nviction of the Chamber of Commerce.\n\u201cThis conviction has been vindicated\nduring the past few years. Washing\nton's private business and industrial\nenterprises are gaining new strength\nand vigor and they are increasing in\nnumber and In volume of their output.\nPlace for Development.\n\u201cThere is a place in the District for\nthe sound development of a great va\nriety of business and industrial enter\nprises which can go forward hand In\nhand with the development of the com\nmunity as the seat of the Federal Gov\nernment.\"\nIn concluding his radio talk Mr.\nDarr outlined the many exhibits plan\nl ned for the sixth annual exposition,\ni which Include displays of lighting and\ni heating by gas and electricity, acces\ni sories for use in these fields, utilities of\ni transportation and telephone organi\nsations. office equipment, house fur\nnlshings, palatable products, and the\nlike. A feature of the exposition will\nbe an exhibit by the Typothetae of\ni Washington, which will incorporate ex\ni htblts of the Government Printing Office\nf and the Bureau of Engraving and\nt Printing. A typewriting and shorthand\ncontest and model aircraft competition\nare also planned for the exposition.\nGEN. BOOTH GIVEN\nHIGH STAFF POST\nBecomes Deputy Chief Under\nMcArthur \u2014Admiral Clu\nverius Promoted.\nImportant changes in assignments In\nthe Army and Navy were made yester\nday when Maj. Gen. Ewing E. Booth,\nassistant chief of staff for supply at\nthe War Department, was detailed by\ndirection of President Hoover as deputy\nchief of stafT of the Army, and Rear\nAdmiral Wat T. Cluverius was as\nsigned by the Navy Department as chief\nof staff of the commander-in-chief of\nthe United States Fleet.\nGen. Booth relieves Maj Gen. Pres\nton Brown, who has been assigned to\nthe Panama Canal military department,\nthe change effective at once. Gen.\nBrown has arranged to sail from New\nOrleans for the Panama Canal Zone\nNovember 15.\nChange Effective Shortly.\nAdmiral Cluverius. now commanding\nbattleship division No. 2 of the Scout\ning Fleet, is to take over his new duties\non November 3 aboard the flagship U. S.\nS. Texas.\nThe selection of Gen. Booth was\nbased on the recommendation of Maj.\nGen. Douglas McArthur, recently desig\nnated as chief of staff, who is ex\npected to reach here and assume that\noffice early in November at the expira\ntion of the term of Gen. Charles R.\nSummerall.\nGen. Booth, a native of Missouri,\nserved with distinction in the Spanish-\nAmerican War and the World War.\nHe began his military service as a cap\ntain in the Ist Colorado Infantry in\nMay, 1898, and served in the World\nWar as a brigadier general in the\nNational Army. He was commissioned\nin the Regular Army as a first lieu\ntenant of Cavalry in February, 1901.\nand reached the grade of major general\nin December, 1929. He is an honor\ngraduate of the Infantry and Cavalry\nSchools and a graduate of the Army\nWar College and the General Staff\nCollege.\nGen. Booth is married and resides\nat the Willard Hotel.\nBorn in New Orleans.\nA native of New Orleans, where he\nwas born December 25, 1874, Admiral\nCluverius was a naval cadet aboard the\nU. S. S. Maine when the vessel was\nsunk in Havana Harbor on February\n15, 1898. For his part in laying mines\nin the North Sea during the World\nWar as the skipper of the U. S. S.\nShawmut, Admiral Cluverius was\nawarded the Distinguished Service\nMedal.\nHe was commandant of midshipmen\nat the Naval Academy from 1919 to\n1921 and attended the Naval War Col\nlege in 1921 and 1922. Following duty\nas commanding officer of the U. S. S.\nSeattle Admiral Cluverius came to\nWashington and served in the office of\nnaval operations, part of the time as\naide to the Secretary of the Navy.\nIn 1926 he commanded the battle\nship West Virginia and then became\ncommandant of the Norfolk, Va\u201e Navy\nYard. Last Summer Admiral Cluverius\nwas in command of the midshipman\npractice cruise.\nFARM WAGES DROP\nWITH EXCESS LABOR\nExtensive Business Depression De\nclared Reflected in Surplus\nof Workers.\nB7 the Associated Press.\nPoor crop prospects, declines In farm\nproduct prices and a 40 per cent excess\nof farm labor brought farm wages on\nOctober 1 to the lowest level since\nJanuary. 1923.\nThe Department of Agriculture said\nyesterday the excessive supply of farm\nhands \u201cis a reflection of the contin\nuance of the present extensive business\ndepression which has scattered unem\nployed Industrial workers throughout\nagricultural sections in search of a live\nlihood.'\u2019\n\u201cThe supply is in excess of the de\nmand in all geographical sections,\" the\nreport continued, \"ranging from an ex\ncess of 24 per cent in the north Atlantic\nStates to 49 per cent in the Bouth Cen\ntral States.\u201d\nThe farm wages index on October 1\nwas placed at 150 per cent of the 1910-\n1914 pre-war level. This index reflected\na drop of 10 points since July 1 this\nyear and a drop of 24 points since Oc\ntober 1, last year. Wages declined\nfrom July 1 to October 1 this year,\nwhereas in the past five years there has\nbeen an average seasonal advance of\n2.6 points during this period.\nDay wages of farm workers not pro\nvided with board now range from abo\\ff\n$3.50 in the northeastern industrial\nStates and $3.40 on the Pacific Coast,\ndown to $1.05 to $1.15 from South Caro\nlina to Mississippi. The North Central\nStates show an average of $2.60 per\nday and the average for the country\nis $2.12. Farm workers provided with\nboard are receiving an average of $1.61\nper day.\nTWO FLYERS HALT\nAT ALBUQUERQUE\nRobert Buck and Laura Ingalls\nFight Snow, Rain and\nHeavy Fog,\nBy the Associated Press.\nALBUQUERQUE, N. Mex., October\n11. \u2014Fighting snow, rain and fog, which\ncaused suspension of traffic on trans\ncontinental air lines to the West, Rob\nert Buck and Laura Ingalls, flyers,\nseeking cross-country records, halted\nhere this afternoon in their race across\nthe United States. Both will remain\novernight.\nMiss Ingalls has 7 hours 13 minutes\nflying time since she hopped off from\nGlendale, Calif., yesterday at 6:13 a m.\n(Pacific standard timei, she reported.\nBuck's compilation shows he is 39 min\nutes ahead of his competitor, with\nelapsed time totaling 6 hours 34\nminutes\nMiss Ingalls, 25, of St. Louis, holds\nthe world record for executing consec\nutive barrel rolls. Earlier in the week\nshe established an East-West trans\ncontinental flight record for women of\n30 hours and 27 minutes elapsed time.\nShe is seeking to better this time on\na West-East flight.\nBuck, 16-year-old aviator of Elizabeth,\nN. J\u201e a few days ago claimed the junior\nEast-West recortf with a mark of 28\nhours. 33 minutes. He is attempting\nto better the junior West-East record.\nChancing to plan their return flights\nEast at the same time, the youth and\nthe woman said they were agreeable to\na friendly race and so far have been\ntiming their take-offs a few minutes\napart.\nDeputy Sheriff in Dual Role.\nRALEIGH, N. C\u201e October 11\nGarland Jones is a deputy sheriff, one\nof whose duties it is to pull a switch\nat State Prison for electrocutions. He\nexecuted Harvey Lawrence, colored.\nThree and one-half hours later he shot\nand killed James Ost*n, colored, in a\nraid on a liquor still near Gamer. A\ncoroner's jury found he had acted in\ndefense of hi* life.\n1 India\u2019s imports and exports are ex\ni pected to total more than $2,000,000,000\nthis year.\nCommands Shifted\n3\nWmrr 'J\nMAJ. GEN. EWING E. BOOTH.\nr-x\n\u25a0B\n\n\n&*\u00a7l| Be j\nJXBk 19H|H\ns\nK i fl\nADMIRAL W AT X. CLUVERIUS.\nCommunist Seriously 111.\nNEW YORK, October 11 (JP).\u2014 Robert\nMinor, Communist candidate for Con\ngress, remained in a critical condition\ntoday at a hospital, where he under\nwent an operation for appendicitis yes\nterday. He was removed a few days\nago under parole from Welfare Island\nPrison where he was serving a sentence\nfor participating in a Communist riot\nlast March.\nr 1 A Our sth Annual\nTomorrow! aunt:\nSj can\u2019t afford to miss... <1 -C\\tV e\nevery item is a real v\nf f value! Check those\nwe otter w lich you need cS> r {d\nCLIP THE COU. s' <y* Vj v fi\u00bbW\u00bb\nastounding I \u2122L\u2122\" V\nsavings in our 1 L/Ca.\nsth annual\nI\nI j ,10,. E\u00abcplional]y Fi,, J\nConsisting of hardwood drop- J j I Inch modern period china\nleaf table and four Windsor style I j closet, oblong extension table and j\nchairs, all strongly I j i I set of 6 chairs\n15179 Overstuffed 3-Pc.j |gg?*9T*i\n\u20141 j I Coupon No. 5\nj $1.98 End Table, strongly made I Bed-Davenport Suite r~~ it\njof hardwood, finished ma- I JL j I $59.00 Secretary Desk and Book- I\nhogany. With this coupon i j case, richly finished in mahogany. .t\nCoupon No. u upholstered with Grade-A Taupe Velour in floral I