s and pure layer felt. Cover- j Main Store, 827-829 7th St. N.W. $14.75 Lane Guaranteed Cedar |I\ning of durable damask in blue and I 7 I Cheat, mothproof and\nwhite design. All sizes. 019 7/1 I I dustproof. With this d>>y Off\nWith this coupon f- /u Store No 2 1213 Good Hope Road SE. I coupon I\n1 1 r r. Call NAtional 8360 1 \u2014\u2014-J\nj ijfi\nWEALTHY AVIATION\nPATRON IS MISSING\nC. V. Bob Sought for Several\nDays in Probe of Two\nNew York Firms.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 11.\u2014The where\nabouts of Charles V. Bob, capitalist and\npatron of aerial explorations, was the\nsubject of both private and official con\njecture today.\nConcern was first caused when Bob,\nwho had been scheduled to fly here from\nChicago, failed to arrive. Later his plane i\nwas found in a Chicago hangar, but it\nwas discovered he had checked out of\nhis hotel on Wednesday.\nHe was flown to Chicago by his regu\nlar pilot, Col. Dean Lamb. Business\nassociates here said he had intended to\nreturn last night with Lamb and Fred- I\nerick C. Russell, whom they described\nas his \u201cright-hand man.\u201d\nAfter articles concerning Bob were\nprinted in the newspapers. Assistant At\ntorney General Watson Washburn an\nnounced his office had been seeking Bob\nfor several days for information con\ncerning two companies it had under\ninvestigation, the Rainbow Luminous\nProducts Co. and Metal and Mining. Inc.\nVisit to Office Fruitless.\nWashburn sent investigators to Bob\u2019s\nBroadway office today to see if they\ncould discover anything about his\nwhereabouts. In the office which they\nsaid also is the office of the Metal and\nMining, they found Ferdinand Pecora,\nformer first assistant district attorney,\nwho is Bob's lawyer, and George L.\nJohnson of River Grove, 111., president\ni of Metal and Mining.\nJohnson was unable to tell them any\nthing about the company, Its books and\nrecords, the whereabouts of the stocks\nin which it dealt or the banks in which\nit made deposits. He said Bob was chair\nman of the company and its affairs\nwere completely in his hands. He said\nRussell, who went to Chicago with Bob,\nwas the only other man who knew any\nthing about the company.\nLast Monday, Washburn said, an\neffort was made to subpoena Bob, but\nat hi* offices it was said he had gone\nto Chicago. On Wednesday Pecora\ncalled en him and said Bob was detain\ned in Chicago by business. On Thurs\nday, Washburn said. Pecora told him\nBob was leaving that afternoon for\nNew York and yetserday he told him\nBob's plane had broken down at some\nunnamed place 200 miles from New\nYork.\nPolice to Aid in Search.\nWashburn said he was interested\nparticularly in Metal and Mining and\nnot so much in Luminous Products,\nwhich has an office in the same build\ning, but separate from the Bob offices.\nExplorer\nBk.\nk\n\u25a0i\nj? j\nNjj\u00a3 x\nJKM H\nIsS\n\u25a0B fl\n'--o;'.--' JR-\n|||i\n\nGRACE THOMPSON SETON.\nj\nHe said he had been informed invest\nors had put $6,000,000 into the company,!\nthe stock of which once reached a high\nof 16>b. once dropped as low as 3%,\nbut rallied after the dividend and closed\nlast night at 6 Vi.\nWashburn said every agency of the\nattorney general's office, including the\nState police, would be utilized in a i\nsearch for Bob and Russell. When they\nare found, he said, they would be served\nwith subpoenas calling for their pres\nence forthwith.\nMAXIMUM SENTENCE\nIS GIVEN GANGSTER\ni By the Associated Press.\nBALTIMORE, October 11.\u2014Willie\nNiemoth, alleged Chicago gangster con\nvicted of participation in a $47,000 hold\nup here in 1926, was sentenced Thurs-\nI day In Criminal Court to 10 years in\nthe penitentiary. It was the heaviest\nsentence possible under the law affect\ning the case.\nFor three years Niemoth fought ex\ntradition from Chicago, but was brought\nhere in June and convicted. A motion\nfor a new trial was rejected a few days\nago by the State Supreme Court.\nNiemoth and two others held up and\nrobbed the paymaster of Henry Sonne\nborn Co. on October 1, 1926, and\nfled in an automobile. Later the car\nwas found abandoned, with one of the\nrobbers on a seat, dead from a bullet\nwound.\nNiemoth testified he was in Chicago\nat the time. Several witnesses idenfi- I\nfled him, however, as a man they had\nseen in the robbery car. I\nB\u20145\nMRS. SETON STARTS\nJOURNEY TO ORIENT\nIn Addition to Collecting\nWriting Material- She Will\nj Make Ethnological Studies.\nThe urge to explore has again taken\nGrace Thompson Seton away from her\nnative land to the far-away corners of\nthe globe. This time it is the call of\nthe East. She sailed this past week\nfrom San Francisco for the Orient,\nwhere, after a brief stop at Honolulu,\nshe will continue her travels on through\nJapan and China, Siam and Malaysia,\nprobably Including in her Itinerary the\nPhilippine Islands.\nMrs. Seton, who is a keen student of\ngovernment, is particularly interested to\nobserve conditions in China. In addition\nj to collecting material for future writ\nings, Mrs. Seton will also make\nethnological studies in the lands the\nvisits.\nMrs. Seton first acquired her love of\nI travel and exploration through her hus\nband, the famous naturalist. Ernest\nj Thompson Seton, whom she accom\npan led on his quests for information z\nI concerning wild animals and theii\nhaunts. About 10 years ago. however\nj Mrs. Seton entered the field of ex\nploration on her own behalf.\nIn the Summer of 1926 Mrs. Seton\nand Mrs. Marshall Field, Jr., were the\nfirst white women to set foot in certain\nremote parts of South America visited\nby the expedition conducted under the\nauspices of the Field Museum ol\nNatural History of Chicago, of which\nthe two women were members. She is\nreputedly the only woman to have\nvisited the Chaco region in Paraguay,\nwhere she collected some interesting\nanimal species She crossed the Andes\ninto Chile. Bolivia and Pent, where she\nstudied the remains of the ancient\nIncas.\nUpon her present Journey, Mrs Seton\nwill visit Cambodia and the mysterious\nruins of Angkor, as well as the out-of- <Z\nj the-way places of Sunda and Banda\nArchipelago. m\nAs national president of the National\nLeague of American Pen Women, as\nwell as by her numerous writings, Mrs\nSeton is widely known in Washington.\n\nIndian Leader Released.\nALLAHABAD. India, October 11 (/Pi\n\u2014Pandit Jawaharlai, Nehru, former\npresident of the Indian National Con- f\ngress, serving a sentence of six months\u2019\nimprisonment for abetting the manu- t\nj facture of contraband salt, was released\nj today from the Nani Jail.\n\nIn one day recently Justice Humph\nl reys of London granted 81 divorces.","height":"25572","width":"19938"}}
